I believe this commit discards all the inventory item, LED, and Power Supply data.

All D-Bus calls in bmcweb must be done asynchronously via async_method_call().  This means that the caller of async_method_call() will immediately proceed without waiting for the D-Bus call to complete.

If nothing additional is done, the caller will attempt to finish filling out the Redfish response without actually having the data from D-Bus.

The solution is to pass a callback to the async method call.  The callback is called when the D-Bus call has completed.  This allows the algorithm to proceed once the data is available.

I believe the change on line 2441 means that getInventoryItems() will call the toplevel callback parameter before the inventory item, LED, and Power Supply data has been obtained from D-Bus.  That means that getSensorData() will be called immediately, and it will fill out the Redfish response without having any of the inventory item, LED, or Power Supply data.

After some testing, I found the error "xyz.openbmc_project.Common.Error.ResourceNotFound" may be caused by the first parameter specifying an non-existent path. In this case, "/xyz/openbmc_project/inventory/system" perhaps does not exist on the device being tested.

To reproduce this error, one can run this code snippet:

    auto bus = sdbusplus::bus::new_default();
    sdbusplus::message::message msg = bus.new_method_call(
        "xyz.openbmc_project.ObjectMapper",
        "/xyz/openbmc_project/object_mapper",
        "xyz.openbmc_project.ObjectMapper",
        "GetSubTreePaths"
    );
    msg.append("      Non-Existent Object Path    ");   //  <---- This causes ResourceNotFound
    msg.append(2);
    msg.append(std::vector<std::string>{
        "xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Item.Bmc"});
    sdbusplus::message::message reply = bus.call(msg, 0);

Or the command

    busctl call xyz.openbmc_project.ObjectMapper /xyz/openbmc_project/object_mapper xyz.openbmc_project.ObjectMapper GetSubTreePaths sias  "  Non-Existent Object Path  " 2 1 "xyz.openbmc_project.Inventory.Item.Bmc"


If this turns out to be the case, one way that might resolve this is in https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-health-monitor/+/45146. It's most likely not the best way to resolve this issue; I would want to see if this works and look forward to comments on how to best fix this.
